Abstract
This paper makes an important contribuon to comparave research by examining data journalism in Spain and Austria.
This paper examines the pracce of data journalism from a triple perspecve: (a) the common features of day-to-day
work, (b) the organizaonal structure and the role of the teams in newsrooms, and (c) the obstacles to and the future
of data-driven reporng. Results from content analysis of data-driven news stories in El pas and Der standard (N = 136)
show dierences and similaries in the covered topics, sources, narrave style, visualizaons, interacve funcons, and
levels of transparency. Interesngly, only 36.8% of the analyzed news stories correspond to the normave expectaons
of transparency by incorporang both sources and methodological details. While the Spanish newspaper shows signi-
cantly higher levels of transparency compared with the Austrian newspaper, both newspapers perform very similarly
when it comes to providing access to raw data, which was the case in only every h news story analyzed. Findings from
focused interviews with the heads of data journalism teams deliver interesng insights into specic challenges that each
news outlet is facing when creang day-to-day data-driven news stories. This research conrms the relevance that data
journalism has achieved in countries such as Spain and demonstrates the eort of journalists in countries without access
to informaon and transparency laws to create data-driven stories.

1. Introducon
Journalism has always relied on data to inform, report, combine sources, or contextualize. However, the connecon of
digitalizaon and datacaon paved the way for a new era for informaon professionals (Mayer-Schnberger; Cukier,
2013). Those changes led to journalisms quantave turn (Coddington, 2015), and it reinforced professional proles
such as the data journalist with an increased focus on measurement, outcomes assessment (Anderson, 2015, p. 363).
The rst reference to the term data journalism was made more than 15 years ago, when Holovaty (2006) menoned
the need to work with spreadsheets to collate the informaon they gathered. This specializaon illustrated how the
media environment was changing and how data represented and inuenced society (Van-Dijck, 2014; Porlezza, 2019).
Arrese (2022) insists that the essence of data journalism comes from economic journalism, especially because of its
purpose: to reduce uncertainty and guide decision-making. Despite idenfying successive iniaves, the term began to
become popular, especially from 2010 onward with Wikileaks and Tim Berners-Lees statements, in which he assured
that the future of journalism lay in data analysis (Howard, 2014; Uskali; Kuu, 2015). The same year, The economist
published a special issue called Data, data everywhere, in which it compared data with oil, as one of the most valuable
resources (Toonders, 2014). At rst glance, there are no signicant dierences between data journalism and other pre-
vious disciplines such as precision journalism and computer-assisted journalism. However, the main disncon lies in the
big data context faced by the journalist and the needs arising from it (Gray; Bounegru; Chambers, 2012; Sandoval-Mar-
n; La-Rosa, 2018; De-Lima-Santos; Mesquita, 2021).
Data-driven journalism pracce and the corresponding academic literature have grown signicantly since 2013 (Ausser-
hofer et al., 2017; Zamith, 2019; Heravi; Lorenz, 2020). The vast majority of papers are limited to specic geographical
areas, thus oering a segmented view. Although there has been a major increase in academic aenon on underrepre-
sented regions (e.g., Mustvairo; Bebawi; Borges-Rey, 2020; Pereira; Mastrella, 2022; Camaj; Marn; Lanosga, 2022;
Kashyap; Mishra; Bhaskaran, 2022), research has mainly focused on countries with a long tradion in data journalism
(Appelgren; Lindn; Van-Dalen, 2020; De-Lima-Santos; Schapals; Bruns, 2020) such as the United Kingdom (e.g., Kni-
ght, 2015; Borges-Rey, 2016; Arias-Robles; Lpez-Lpez, 2020; Tong, 2021) and the United States (e.g., Parasie; Darigal,
2012; Fink; Anderson, 2015; Zamith, 2019). For this reason, Fink and Anderson (2015), Splendore et al. (2016), Cherui-
yot, Baack and Ferrer-Conill (2019), and Wright, Zamith, and Bebawi (2019) advocate for cross-naonal comparave
studies to provide in-depth understanding of the development of this specializaon and to explore the nuances of the
phenomenon.
A comparison between Spain and Austria seems parcularly suitable for this purpose: both are democrac sociees with
well-developed media systems. Lile specic research on Spanish data journalism has been published, and moreover
especially focused on specic topics such as polics, without delving into the features of day-to-day data stories and
professional rounes (Rojas-Torrijos; Rivera-Hernndez, 2016; Teruel-Rodrguez; Blanco-Caslla, 2016; Crdoba-Ca-
bs, 2018; Crdoba-Cabs; Garca-Borrego; Lpez-Marn, 2020; Rubio-Jordn, 2021; Arias-Robles; Carvajal, 2022).
Likewise, there are no studies related to Austrian data journalism, so this paper aims to address this research need and
provide ndings to migate this gap.
According to the categorizaon established by Hallin and Mancini (2004), Spain belongs to the polarized pluralist model
and Austria to the democrac corporast model. Nevertheless, data show how these countries converge in terms of a
high concentraon of media owners, the decline of newspaper circulaon, and the restricons on access to data due
to limitaons from legislaon (Figl, 2017; Salaverra; Gmez-Baveiredo, 2017; Grnangerl; Trappel; Tomaz, 2021). Al-
barrn (2009) and Ohlsson (2015) already introduced the idea of the hybridizaon of models and the European trend
toward homogenizaon.
The core objecve of this study is to explore data journalism pracce in Austria and Spain. More specically, this study
aims to (1) assess the content of data journalism in Spain and Austria by analyzing data-driven news stories in the Spa-
nish newspaper El pas and the Austrian newspaper Der standard and (2) explore work rounes as well as the obstacles
to and future scenarios of data-driven reporng by interviewing the heads of data journalism of these news outlets.
1.1. Data journalism and access to informaon
Data journalism is a relavely young eld, so achieving an exhausve denion is rather challenging. In the literature, se-
veral aempts to dene data journalism can be idened. Howard (2014, p. 4), for instance, considered data journalism
to be a process associated with data science that encompasses gathering, cleaning, organizing, analysing, visualizing,
and publishing data to support the creaon of acts of journalism. Meanwhile, Veglis and Bratsas (2017, p. 111) speci-
ed that data journalists engage in the process of
wring arcles based on the informaon and embedding visualizaons in the arcles that help readers to
understand the signicant of the story or allow them to pinpoint data that relate to them.
Heravi (2018, p. 3) stated that data journalism consists of
nding stories in data stories that are of interest to the public and presenng these stories in the most appro-
priate manner for public use and reuse.

Following Coddingtons denion, herein, we unders-
tand data journalism to be the result of a convergence
between dierent knowledge areas and pracces, i.e.,
as a
hybrid form [of journalism] that encompasses stascal analysis, computer science, visualizaon and web de-
sign, and reporng (Coddington, 2015, p. 335).
Three common components can be discerned in all of these: the exploraon of databases, the proccessing of data, and
the communicaon of results.
Focusing on the features of data journalism projects, empirical studies have shown that data-driven news stories stron-
gly rely on government and instuonal sources (Karlsson, 2010; Parasie; Darigal, 2012; Knight, 2015; De-Maeyer et al.,
2015; Cushion; Lewis; Callaghan, 2017; Loosen; Reimer; Schmidt, 2017; Tandoc; Oh, 2017; Lowrey; Hou, 2018; Stalph,
2018; Young; Hermida; Fulda, 2018; Appelgren, 2018; Hyder; Nahid, 2019; Zamith, 2019; Zhang; Feng, 2019; Crdo-
ba-Cabs, 2020; Rubio-Jordn, 2021). The main purpose of data-driven stories is to inform and present data through
narraon and visualizaon (Loosen; Reimer; Schmidt, 2017; Ojo; Heravi, 2018; Young; Hermida; Fulda, 2018; Crdo-
ba-Cabs, 2020; Rubio-Jordn, 2021). The author-driven style is the most common narrave structure applied (Loosen;
Reimer; Schmidt, 2017; Ojo; Heravi, 2018). Regarding transparency, prior research has found that data stories only
rarely show transparency elements such as access to the raw data (Lowrey; Hou, 2018; Young; Hermida; Fulda, 2018;
Stalph, 2018; Zhang; Feng, 2019; Zamith, 2019; Porlezza; Splendore, 2019; Crdoba-Cabs; Garca-Borrego, 2021; Cha-
parro-Domnguez; Daz-Campo, 2021). Although the ndings in terms of visualizaon in data-driven projects are mixed,
stac gures and limited use of interacve funcons seem common (Loosen; Reimer; Schmidt, 2017; Tandoc; Oh, 2017;
Young; Hermida; Fulda, 2018; Appelgren, 2018; Stalph, 2018; Ojo; Heravi, 2018; Appelgren, 2018; Crdoba-Cabs;
Garca-Borrego, 2020).
The development of data journalism depends heavily on the context in which it emerges. The establishment of transpa-
rency and access-to-informaon laws encourages the emergence of data-driven projects (Parasie; Darigal, 2012; Appel-
gren; Nygren, 2014; Uskali; Kuu, 2015; De-Maeyer et al., 2015; Tabary; Provost; Troer, 2016; Appelgren; Salaverra,
2018; Sandoval-Marn; La-Rosa, 2018; Porlezza; Splendore, 2019; Tong; Zuo, 2021; Camaj; Marn; Lanosga, 2022;
Kashyap; Mishra; Bhaskaran, 2022; Tong, 2022). Hence, the most well-developed and successful data journalism is
found in countries with laws that ensure compliance with these principles (Howard, 2014; Corts-del-lamo; Luengo;
Elas, 2018).
In the European Union, regulaons regarding access to public documents were adopted in 2001, but the implementaon
of these regulaons diers by country (Appelgren; Salaverra, 2018). Thereaer, the European Commission adopted
the public sector informaon direcve in 2003 (Direcve 2003/98/EC), which encouraged the reuse of public data and
enabled access in digital format.
In Spain, the law on transparency, access to public informaon, and good governance was approved in 2013, and work is
currently underway to dra the corresponding regulaon together with civil society. However, this law is not in line with
European Court of Human Rights jurisprudence, and it lacks control mechanisms to ensure compliance (Snchez-Calero;
Mancinas-Chvez, 2017; Appelgren; Salaverra, 2018). In Austria, the constuon guarantees freedom of informaon,
but there is no specic law regulang transparency. The European Convenon on Human Rights guarantees access to
informaon, but the Austrian constuon limits this right by requiring that instuons apply discreon (Figl, 2017;
Grnangerl; Trappel; Tomaz, 2021). This may explain why Austria was at the boom of the global right to informaon
ranking in 2022, with 33 points out of 150 (RTI, 2022). In this regard, it is considered to be one of the weakest countries
in the world. Meanwhile, Spain scored 73 out of 150 points.
In Austria, data journalists are sll a rare species (Figl, 2017, p. 5). Unl a few years ago, data journalism was only
pracced in small newsrooms such as Dossier, the public broadcaster ORF, and the naonal newspaper Der standard.
Ocially, in 2021, the Austrian Press Agency (APA) set up the Data + Graphics team, which brings together experts in
data, infographics, design, and web developers. This is expected to provide visibility and value to the discipline. The rst
examples of data journalism in Spain emerged within organizaons such as Fundacin Civio or Medialab-Prado in 2011.
El condencial was the rst media outlet to set up a data journalism team in 2013. However, the main generalist newspa-
per in Spain (El pas) did not publish data journalism stories unl 2017, while the public broadcaster (RTVE) set up their
data team in 2019. Research focused on Spain shows a progressive upward trend in data journalism. However, except
for digital-nave media such as El condencial, Spanish newspapers did not commit to data journalism beyond specic
projects unl 2015. The health pandemic associated with the coronavirus highlighted the relevance of data journalism,
as well as the rise of stories based on gures in Spain (Crdoba-Cabs; Garca-Borrego; Lpez-Marn, 2020; Costa-Sn-
chez; Lpez-Garca, 2020; Sanahuja; Lpez, 2021).

2. Methods
To answer these research quesons, we combined quantave and qualitave methods. First, we conducted a quan-
tave content analysis of data-driven news stories published in El pas (Spain) and Der standard (Austria) to provide an
overview of how data are used in news stories from these news outlets (N =136). Second, we employed interviews with
two members of the data journalism teams of El pas (Spain) and Der standard (Austria) to beer understand the process
of how journalists select and create news stories using data-driven techniques.
2.1. Content analysis
The quantave content analysis focused on exploring the full content of data-driven news stories published online from
1 January to 30 June 2021, in the newspapers El pas (Spain) and Der standard (Austria) (N = 136). Content analysis as a
methodological tool enables one to understand the structure of stories as well as their basic components and operaon
(Igartua, 2006). These two newspapers were selected because they are the naonal newspapers most trusted by the
populaon 48% and 69%, respecvely according to the Digital news report (Reuters Instute, 2021). They both have a
data team in their newsroom and the highest online reach (21% and 20%, respecvely) in the last year (Reuters Instute,
2021). We created a codebook consisng of formal categories (medium, date of publicaon, headline, secon, and link)
and categories that aimed to capture the content of data-driven news stories. Specically, the proposed categories can
be grouped into three dimensions: story features, data, and visualizaons (Table 1).

The variables examined in the rst dimension are specied below.
Topics
Based on dierent categorizaons proposed by Loosen, Reimer, and Schmidt (2017), Tandoc and Oh (2017), and Stalph
(2018), the following list of topics was created: (1) polics; (2) society; (3) economics and business; (4) health, science,
and environment; (5) educaon; (6) sports; (7) culture and art; and (8) entertainment.
Sources
Building on prior research (Knight, 2015; Loosen; Reimer; Schmidt, 2017), we encoded the types of sources used in the
analyzed news stories. We coded the number of included personal sources, the types of sources, and the aribuon.
Narrave style
It was coded as follows: (a) explanatory or author-driven style, that is, a heavy message load and reduced interacvity;
(b) exploratory or reader-driven style, that is, no specic order and free interacon; and (c) hybrid, that is, a combinaon
(Segel; Heer, 2010).
Type of story
Building on the conceptualizaon of Rogers (2014) and based on the type of data and the methods employed, we disn-
guished between the following types of data journalism projects: (1) by just the facts (includes public data and produces
a visualizaon), (2) data-driven news stories (refers to issues that are in the public eye and reveals the numbers behind
the news), (3) analysis and background (explains the facts behind the news by providing a thorough analysis and detailed
informaon), and (4) deep invesgaons (in-depth research on large datasets).
Temporal dimension, focus, purpose, way of communicang
Both the me and focus dimensions were delimited according to criteria from Davenport (2014). In line with Gray, Bou-
negru, and Chambers (2012), we selected the purpose of the story, while the way in which data were communicated
was determined by using the classicaon from Bradshaw (2011): visualize, narrate, socialize, humanize, personalize,
and ulize.
Data
Focusing on the data dimension, we also analyzed the number, the type, and the aribuon of data sources (Knight,
2015; Loosen; Reimer; Schmidt, 2017). Moreover, the level of transparency in terms of access to raw data and incorpo-
raon of methodological details was also assessed (Hayes; Singer; Ceppos, 2007; Karlsson, 2010; Parasie; Darigal, 2012;
Tandoc; Oh, 2017; Young; Hermida; Fulda, 2018; Stalph, 2018; Lowrey; Hou, 2018; Zamith, 2019; Zang; Feng, 2019).
Visualizaons
Finally, building on Crdoba-Cabs and Garca-Borrego (2020), we coded the type of visualizaon as the third dimension of
Table 1: (1) tables and lists, (2) stac graphs, (3) interacve graphs, (4) maps with or without interacvity, (5) visual resour-
ces, (6) animaons, and (7) infographics. In so doing, we also examined the acons that the audience can conduct with the
visualizaons, i.e., the interacvity (Schulmeister, 2003; Yi; Ah-Kang; Stasko, 2007; Boy, Deene; Fekete, 2015).

2.3. Interviews
We conducted focused interviews with members of the data journalism teams of El pas and Der standard. This techni-
que is considered the most suitable approach to deal with innovaons in this area (Arias-Robles; Lpez-Lpez, 2020),
and it enabled us to explore the posion of each media outlet. The interviewees were located and contacted through
Twier and corporave email. Owing to the explorave nature of this study, we talked to only one journalist per news-
room. On the basis of relevance criteria and availability, we interviewed Daniele Grasso, Coordinator of the Data Journa-
lism Unit at El pas, and Michael Matzenberger, Head of Data Journalism / Interacve, at Der standard. The interviews,
lasng between 60 and 75 minutes, were conducted online via Google Meet between October and December 2021. The
conversaons were recorded and manually transcribed. A quesonnaire comprising 16 quesons was used, organized
into three themac areas related to the research quesons: (a) the organizaonal structure of data teams and the com-
mon features of day-to-day data-driven stories; (b) quality data journalism, access to informaon, and protability; and
(c) the current status and future developments of data-driven reporng.
3. Results
3.1. Features of data-driven stories
The results of the content analysis reveal the dierences between and similaries of the data journalism pracces in
Spain and Austria. In total, 136 data-driven stories were published during the period examined: 99 in El pas (72.8%) and
37 in Der standard (27.2%). On average, the names of two journalists were menoned per news story (ME=2; standard
deviaon [SD]=1.84).
In the total sample analyzed, health, science, and environment was the dominant topic (36.8%). In this context, stories
that examined data about the coronavirus pandemic were especially common (Table 2). The results highlighted the sig-
nicant dierences between the two newspapers analyzed (ES=0.443). While El pas published more data-driven news
stories about polics (36.4%), in Der standard, business (24.3%) and social issues (18.3%) were the most frequently
covered topics.

3.2. Organizaon of the teams and creaon of data-driven stories
The El pas data team is formed of three journalists with dierent proles, integrated into the Visual Narraves group,
which is made up of around ten people, including gures such as designers and developers. This team plays a cross-func-
onal role in the newsroom, and they usually work together in all steps. The Der standard data unit has a similar struc-
ture, with four members with well-dened proles. However, only the head of the team has a permanent full-me
contract, which makes it dicult to create pieces on a connuous basis. As at El pas, it has a transversal role, but there is
a clear division of tasks, especially regarding technical funcons such as programming, analysis, or interacon. Although
the producon process of data-driven stories is not standardized, both the Spanish and Austrian newspapers include
four key steps:
(1) Choice and concepon of the project, which consists of focusing on the topic, searching for sources of informaon,
and previous research.
(2) Analysis of the dataset, which is the most extensive stage because the framework is established here; this includes
cleaning up the gures and asking the right quesons about the data.

The team spirit at the Spanish media outlet is very similar to at the Austrian one. Nevertheless, the main dierence is

We try not to tread on the daily journalism because data analysis requires me and that does not t in with the
speed of publicaon of a newspaper. From the beginning, we made it clear to our bosses: if they want good work,
it cannot be done in one day. That does not mean that we are not able to produce arcles in a morning as we have
done with Covid or elecon results.
The Der standard data team ensure that they can oer immediacy because they mostly depend on other secons. To
a lesser extent especially when they propose their own topics they publish stories with a longer producon process.
For El pas, the main obstacles to data journalism pracce are the formats in which the public instuons publish their
data hindering their reuse and the lack of availability of certain gures. In Austria, there are even greater problems. In
addion to immediacy, there are also limitaons related to access to informaon. Marzenberger explained,
We denitely have a real problem in Austria. The Covid pandemic showed that authories hide data and ignore
our enquiries. Even some available and anonymized data is restrained under the cloak of privacy. On top of that
we have to add endless bureaucracy to get access to public databases, which makes our work more dicult and
makes it not worthwhile to spend me requesng data.
3.3. Quality data journalism, access to informaon, and protability
El pas maintains that quality data journalism work should be interesng, useful, and transparent. Grasso stated that
there are no elements that determine the quality of a project; the main objecve pursued by its publicaon is
what makes it a good piece.
However, he insisted on the importance of incorporang how data is collected and how these conclusions have been
reached to provide solvency to the arcle. In the same vein, Der standard also states that a good data story must comply
with journalisc principles, and its quality will be determined by the news value of the informaon.
Both the Spanish and the Austrian newspapers agree that data journalism is more well-recognized and developed in
countries with eecve access-to-informaon laws. Although the Spanish legislaon has its shortcomings, the lack of
guidelines in terms of access to informaon in Austria makes data journalism pracces more dicult.
[In Spain] The transparency council should have more power. It should not be an agency that only urges on
paper, but it should enforce the law. That could mean a leap in quality and to duck out once quesoned by the
cizen would be impossible for the instuons, Grasso said.
Michael Matzenberger explained that
some opposion pares and civil acvists have been ghng for years to bring a transparency law on track, yet
we do not know if and to what extent it will become true.
The El pas journalist asserted that their readers are in-
terested in data journalism based on reading me and
the online reach of their publicaons. This has been de-
monstrated with the current subscripon model of this
media outlet, too. He also stated that this specializaon
is protable because it helps to add dierenaon from the compeon and allows them to build dierent and varied
stories. The same is true for Der standard, which claimed that data-driven stories published during the pandemic are the
most visited pages in their history and that these works have demonstrated the need for reliable data to make decisions.
However, the team members do not feel suciently valued in their own newsroom.
Our colleagues come to us to improve their stories, but they do not see us as indispensable. It would not really
maer if our team broke away, Matzenberger stated.

4. Discussion and conclusions
The aim of this study was to explore data-driven journalism in terms of the content of news stories and journalisc prac-
ces and rounes. The results of this study present strong connecons with previous work, but this study allows us to
delve deeper into the state of data journalism in underexplored countries such as Spain and Austria. The ndings from
the content analysis and interviews reect the disparity of contexts in which data journalism is carried out, the common
features, the organizaonal structure, the limitaons, and the prospects for the specializaon in these countries.
The analysis reveals a general prole of the works published in Der standard and El pas and highlights the similaries
of and dierences between these two newspapers (RQ1). Health, science, and environment is the prevailing topic. This
conrms that this topic is a determining issue corresponding to the me of publicaon. They coincide in giving more
space to arcles about the coronavirus pandemic, but dier in oering space to polics which is more represented in
El pas and to economy or social issues which is more represented in Der standard. These dierences reect the trans-
versality of the tool, which is adaptable to any themac area (RQ1a).
Although adding personal sources is uncommon in day-to-day data journalism, it is more frequent at the Austrian outlet.
In regard to incorporang, the vast majority opt for experts in a eld to complete the informaon. As regards narrave
style, Der standard chose an explanatory structure (Loosen; Reimer; Schmidt, 2017; Ojo; Heravi, 2018), while El pas
preferred to combine explanatory and exploratory styles with some freedom for interacon (Crdoba-Cabs; Garca-Bo-
rrego; Lpez-Marn, 2020).
The projects are almost enrely data-driven stories whose main goal is to inform and to explain what happens. The scant
presence of deep invesgaons during the period under review reveals the pressure for immediacy and a lack of me
to deal with other issues. The most common way of communicang numerical informaon is to combine narrave and
visualizaon (Loosen; Reimer; Schmidt, 2017; Ojo; Heravi, 2018; Young; Hermida; Fulda, 2018; Crdoba-Cabs, 2020;
Rubio-Jordn, 2021). Data journalism arcles can be displayed through a variety of forms. However, it has been demons-
trated that visualizaon plays a key role in this discipline.
The analyzed data-driven stories incorporated two data sources on average, and they mainly relied on government sour-
ces, which is in line with previous research from other countries (Parasie; Darigal, 2012; Knight, 2015; De-Maeyer et al.,
2015; Cushion; Lewis; Callaghan, 2017; Loosen; Reimer; Schmidt, 2017; Stalph, 2018; Young; Hermida; Fulda, 2018;
Appelgren, 2018; Hyder; Nahid, 2019). The problems regarding access to public informaon in Austria are reected in
the use of the news outlets own sources. Unlike El pas, Der standard relied more on its own surveys and experiments to
produce its own data for its news stories. This strategy allowed it to overcome the opacity of the Austrian administraon.
Although transparency is considered to be a fundamental element in data journalism stories, this characterisc is scarce
in day-to-day arcles according to previous studies (Lowrey; Hou, 2018; Young; Hermida; Fulda, 2018; Stalph, 2018;
Zhang; Feng, 2019; Zamith, 2019; Crdoba-Cabs; Garca-Borrego, 2021). While the vast majority of arcles cite sour-
ces directly, linking to datasets and adding a methodological secon remains rare. Zamith (2019, p. 15) stated that
journalists may not priorize leading readers to
source material when aempng to meet deadli-
nes during their day-to-day work or acvely resist
ceding too much autonomy through over-sha-
ring.

In this sense, El pas diers from Der standard. The Spa-
nish outlet meets the idealized form of transparency on
more occasions (RQ1b). This may be due to the lack of
resources, me, and knowledge to provide such open-
ness (Crdoba-Cabs; Garca-Borrego, 2021) or, as men-
oned by Porlezza and Splendore (2019, p. 1246), be-
cause of the fear of free-riding by the competors, which could involve copying or replicang their work.
The strategy in terms of visualizaons and interacvity also diers (RQ1c). While El pas added interacve graphs, Der
standard opted for stac graphs. Despite these divergences, the ndings reinforce the idea of reduced interacvity (Loo-
sen; Reimer; Schmidt, 2017; Young; Hermida; Fulda, 2018; Stalph, 2018; Ojo; Heravi, 2018; Appelgren, 2018; Crdo-
ba-Cabs; Garca-Borrego, 2020). This decrease in interacvity is closely aligned with the addion of simpler and more
basic interacve features in visualizaons, such as exploraon. As pointed out by Appelgren (2018),
The illusion of interacvity thus replaces real interacvity.
The projects increasingly employ perceived interacvity, which gave the audience a sense of control, while the author
actually retained full control.
The interviews conrmed that the context strongly condions how data journalism is carried out (Appelgren; Nygren,
2014; Appelgren; Salaverra, 2018; Sandoval-Marn; La-Rosa, 2018; Porlezza; Splendore, 2019). On the one hand, the
incipient status of data journalism in Austria is mainly due to the lack of guidelines in terms of access to informaon
(RQ2). Moreover, there is an absence of awareness of their value, which implies a lack of recognion even within their
own newspaper. As Tong (2022, p. 2795) stated,
Data journalists experse, together with the increasing internal recognion and their compelling data stories,
helps them establish cultural authority.
On the other hand, at El pas, the working schedule is respected and data journalism is used as a feature to dierenate
it from the compeon. The arcles produced during the analyzed period reveal the dierence in this regard (99 news
stories published in El pas and 37 in Der standard). The situaon of Austrian data journalism is more similar to that in
Arab countries (Lewis; Nashmi, 2019; Mutsvairo; Bebawi; Borges-Rey, 2020) than to that in European countries. Aus-
trian data journalists face all the obstacles menoned in the scienc literature, both internal within the newsrooms
and external related to the context (Appelgren; Lindn; Van-Dalen, 2019; Kashyap; Bhaskaran; Mishra, 2020).
The data teams based on the number of workers and the producon process of a data journalism story are similar in El
pas and Der standard. Although the inverted pyramid proposed by Bradshaw (2011) is called into queson (Albert-Trini-
dad, 2020), these ndings show that data-driven arcles are produced according to these phases. The dierences lie in
the organizaonal structure of the data teams and in the contractual relaonships with each company. Data journalists
in El pas work together in all steps and have permanent full-me contracts. However, a division of tasks prevails in Der
standard, and the members of the data journalism team are hired part-me.
The percepons about the future of data journalism are in line with Stalph and Borges-Rey (2018) and kstrm and
Westlund (2019): Data will become an inherent part of journalism, and it will be essenal to all journalisc publicaons
(RQ3). Journalists at both El pas and Der standard believe that data journalism will grow and evolve. Nevertheless, obs-
tacles in Austria are expected to connue to limit the pracce of data journalism.
This study is not free of limitaons. First, our sample for the content analysis was limited. We were only able to analyze
one newspaper per country. Hence, future studies should extend such analysis to other newspapers that pracce data
journalism in dierent countries. In addion, it would be interesng to analyze changes over me and to deepen our
understanding of the impact of data journalism on society.
Notwithstanding these limitaons, this study was able to deliver important inial insights into day-to-day data jour-
nalism content and work rounes in Spain and Austria. The pracce of data journalism in Austria and Spain mainly
diers because of the context in which it is carried out.
This research conrms the relevance that this speciali-
zaon is currently acquiring in countries such as Spain
and demonstrates the challenges that journalists face in
countries without access to informaon and transparen-
cy laws to build good stories with data.
